<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-09-19T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-09-19T05:00:00-05:00" n="739" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d739">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">852.00/3208: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bowers</hi></persName>), <hi rend="italic">Then in France, to the <gloss type="to">Secretary
                                        of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">St.
                                            Jean de Luz</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-09-19T11:00:00+01:00">September 19, 1936—11
                                        a.m.</date><lb/>[Received September 19—8:43 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>113. At meeting Diplomatic Corps Friday evening unanimously decided
                                to ignore suggestion concerning Madrid. British, French, Argentine
                                and other nationals with Embassies open there with Chargé <pb facs="0822" n="723" xml:id="pg_723"/> d’ Affaires took position
                                suggestion could not apply to them. Am still convinced it was aimed
                                at Italy, Germany and Portugal, who have closed Embassies in Madrid
                                and moved to Alicante.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bowers</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>